y apologies...</span><hr size=1> Took a few days to get back to a computer.<br><br>Your argument presupposes that my entire rationale is the stream-lined and efficient incorporation of facts into my life with the greatest possible ease, and that this rationale drives my desire for the truth to be reported.  Yes, I want my facts, just like every other intelligent person on the planet, including you.  My desire for the facts to be reported to me through the media, however, seems to leave a sour taste in your mouth. Thus, I'll address this.<br><br>The reporting of the media is not necessarily the tell-all, end all source for information. On this I agree.  The problem is that the media holds great influence over the path of society's collective focus in the world.  I don't mean the &quot;masses&quot; even, but most individuals, even highly educated individuals, expect the greatest amount of factual information in their lives to come from the media.  This puts a responsibility on the media to provide facts, I argue.  <br><br>Regardless of my feelings, though, the media (in many forms) has, does and will continue to create a distinctly authorized view of the world, society, animals, religion, everything.  This is done, often unknowingly, by including and not including stories about certain topics. This, I agree, can be rectified through greater research. Unfortunately, this world-view is also created by deciding what does and does not get investigated, due in large part to assumed societal interest. Little interest, little money, no story.  Ideally, with no threat of bankruptcy over their head, reporters could investigate every story they wish to, as well as publish it all.  In reality, we both know this can't happen.  I just don't see the point in giving up on the ideal and saying it's our own laziness that we don't find out about these things that no one investigates.  <br><br>Of course, this also assumes reporters with a naturally inquisitive nature, as opposed to reporters trying simply to feed a family or, sometimes, make a lot of money.  It all comes down to journalistic integrity, and I think journalism has fallen short of this integrity of late, in large part due to economic factors tied to society's displeasure in reading/seeing things they'd rather not.<br><br>I hope even you realize the danger of simply allowing the discourse of journalism to sink into a mirror of the whims of the majority or government.  <br><br>glade <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ukytherion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kytherion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 358<br> <font color=#E9D756>(1/8/02 7:22:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=259.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> baaaaa</span><hr size=1> &quot;I hope even you realize the danger of simply allowing the discourse of journalism to sink into a mirror of the whims of the majority or government. &quot;<br><br><br>Not allowing the government to control the media has been a subtext of most of my posts to this thread. Let's use our own ideas for this, yes?<br><br>And so then we come to the crux of your problem. You distrust the majority. You don't feel the &quot;masses&quot; should control it.<br><br>And yet you feel the media should empower those very same masses by GIVING them the truth? If the majority are not to be trusted, why tell them the truth?<br><br>Apparently, you see no contradiction with this, but the contradiction is there. You don't want them to have the power, and yet you demand that they be given the power.<br><br><br><br>And if we do decide to give the truth, who decides what that truth will be? As Pilate said, what is truth?<br><br>Will YOU determine the truth for them? Who aspires to be 